2. EDA¶

2.1. Import Modules¶

Import relevant modules in one place.

In [1]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import statsmodels.api as sm

import seaborn as sns
sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(16,8)}) # set the figure size for all sns plots
sns.set_style('whitegrid')

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from matplotlib.axes._axes import _log as matplotlib_axes_logger 
matplotlib_axes_logger.setLevel('ERROR') # to hide matplot lib errors

2.3.2 The variable names¶

  • date - This timestamp is converted to NY EST Standard Time
  • close - This is the closing price of the time period

2.3.6 State which variables will be considered as INPUTS and OUTPUTS to a predictive model¶

Since this is a forecasing problem, I will be using historical date and close values to predict the future close value.

LOG Transformation!¶

close is log-transfoirmed closing price. I chose to keep it as 'close' to avoid changing all the code. close_orig is original closing price.

In [35]:
df['close_orig'] = df['close']
df['close'] = np.log(df['close'])
df.head()

2.4.5 Lag plots¶

In [36]:
# daily
lags_use = [1, 7, 10, 14, 20, 50, 100, 182, 365]

fig, ax = plt.subplots(3, 3, figsize=(12, 12), sharex=True, sharey=True)

ax = ax.ravel()

for k in range(len(lags_use)):
    pd.plotting.lag_plot( daily_series, lag=lags_use[k], ax=ax[k] )
    ax[k].plot( ax[k].get_xlim(), ax[k].get_ylim(), 'k--')
    ax[k].set_title('lag: ' + str(lags_use[k]) )

plt.show()
In [37]:
# weekly
lags_use = [1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 10, 12, 26, 52]

fig, ax = plt.subplots(3, 3, figsize=(12, 12), sharex=True, sharey=True)

ax = ax.ravel()

for k in range(len(lags_use)):
    pd.plotting.lag_plot( weekly_series, lag=lags_use[k], ax=ax[k] )
    ax[k].plot( ax[k].get_xlim(), ax[k].get_ylim(), 'k--')
    ax[k].set_title('lag: ' + str(lags_use[k]) )

plt.show()

2.4.7 Time Series Decomposition¶

Weekly¶
In [45]:
# weekly - full data
weekly_decomposition = sm.tsa.seasonal_decompose(
    weekly_series, model='additive')

plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = 18,8
plt.show()

fig = weekly_decomposition.plot()
In [46]:
# weekly - last 2 years
weekly_decomposition_2y = sm.tsa.seasonal_decompose(
    weekly_series[-104:], model='additive') # subsetting from the end

plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = 18,8
plt.show()

fig = weekly_decomposition_2y.plot()

Compare the observed and seasonally adjusted trends.

In [47]:
weekly_2y_decomp = pd.DataFrame({
    'observed': weekly_decomposition_2y.observed, 
    'seasonal_adjusted': weekly_decomposition_2y.observed - weekly_decomposition_2y.seasonal
    },
    index=weekly_series[-104:].index)

sns.relplot( data=weekly_2y_decomp, kind='line', aspect=2.5 )
plt.show()
